  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 12.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Therefore thus saith the Lord God of Israel, Behold, I am bringing such evil upon Jerusalem and Judah, that whosoever heareth of it, both his ears shall tingle.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " \"As a sharp discordant note,\" says Bahr, \"pains one's ears, so the news of this harsh punishment shall give pain to all who hear of it.\" The phrase is one never uttered by any other lips than those of Jehovah (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 3:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 19:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). \"It denotes\" (Keil) \"such a judgment as has never been heard of before, and excites alarm and horror.\" Not the Jews only, but the other neighboring nations, when they heard of the sufferings endured in the siege (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 25:8",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), and the severities exercised upon the king (ver. 7.) and the city (vers. 9, 10) and. the inhabitants (ver. 11), would have a thrill of pain go through them at the hearing, partly unselfish, partly perhaps selfish, since the treatment that was dealt out to others might also be reserved for them. 2 Kings 21:12",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "The Lord therefore announced through the prophets, to the rebellious and idolatrous nation, the destruction of Jerusalem and the deliverance of Judah into the hands of its enemies; but, as is added in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 33:10",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", they paid no heed to them. The prophets who foretold this terrible judgment are not named. According to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Chronicles 33:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", their utterances were entered in the annals of the kings. Habakkuk was probably one of them, since he (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Habakkuk 1:5",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") predicted the Chaldaean judgment as a fact which excited astonishment and appeared incredible. The Amorites are mentioned in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "2 Kings 21:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " instar omnium as the supporters of the Canaanitish ungodliness, as in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Kings 21:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", etc. - The phrase, \"that whosoever heareth it, both his ears may tingle,\" denotes such a judgment as has never been heard of before, and excites alarm and horror (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 Samuel 3:11",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " and ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Jeremiah 19:3",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). The Keri שׁמעהּ is a correction, to bring the pronom. suff. into conformity with the noun רעה so far as the gender is concerned, whereas in the Chethb שׁמעיו the masculine suffix is used in the place of the feminine, as is frequently the case.",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]